This isn't a criticism of the {tcltk} implementation in #RStats - it's complete and powerful.

It's an observation of the level of knowledge required to interface with GUI layout frameworks.

#tcltk

R-SIG-GUI archives indicate that it's a dead horse.

#RStats https://t.co/UgP0eVc0Hf

Warning - if you're not at all interested/curious about {tcltk} GUIs, I'd suggested adding a twitter mute for the #tcltk tag!

This week I think I'll have a lot to say about it as I try to learn enough to do something useful (useless?) with it.

#RStats #brainfarts
#RStats

#tcltk can be themed to look quite pleasant.

Here are some flat themes for tcltk inspired by Bootstrap

https://t.co/sPuEiyGbnL

#RStats https://t.co/DzVRKaHZ3k

The first thing I'll say about {tcltk} pkg in #RStats - the documentation is "challenging"

e.g.  manual for "creating a window" (& most other funcs) just has "..." args, no info on what these might be & a note saying "Please refer to Tcl/Tk documentation"

:(

#tcltk https://t.co/OW1Tk55xsN

#tcltk conceptual difficulty: 

* All elements *must* be assigned a parent when created.
* But this does not mean that the element is positioned within the parents layout.
* A completely separate layout command must be done !

#RStats https://t.co/csEfLnTRHg

@mdsumner Shiny serves that large segment of the #RStats market which wants "show my analysis plots with sliders to the world in a web browser".

But doesn't suit those wanting to write 80s era Drum Machine clones :)

{tcltk} has a VERY high count of WTFs/minute.

e.g.
> library(tcltk)
> text_var <- tclVar("")
> tclvalue(text_var) <- "Hello #RStats"
> as.character(text_var)
[1] "::RTcl1"

#RStats https://t.co/zstdw9IXrr

#RStats hot tip for macOS if you create a lot of projects:

Create "*.Rproj" files from the command line and open in Rstudio

$ mkdir funky
$ cd funky
$ echo "Version: 1.0" > funky.Rproj
$ open funky.Rproj

{tcltk} 

Two images, both alike in energy in fair #RStats where we lay our scene! https://t.co/GksXOKoO3f

{tcltk} in #RStats exposes *ALL* the nitty gritty details of #tcltk.

This makes it powerful and flexible, but utterly incomprehensible if you've never learnt tcl/tk.

It'd be the equivalent of Shiny asking you to understand browser internals in order to write an app.

1-to-1 mapping between TCL<->R, + parent required at creation time, lead to *3* separate funcs just to place element in window:

1. create an object with a parent
2. pack the object within the parent
3. configure how the object is packed within the parent
